<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><p>Oxygen exhibits structural phase transformation from non-metallic -O2 phase into metallic</p></div>
			</abstract>
		</profileDesc>
	</teiHeader>
	<text xml:lang="en">
		<body>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><p>Unconventional superconductivity in -phase of oxygen compressed to megabar pressure I. Introduction Jörg Wittig <ref type="bibr" target="#b0">[1]</ref> heralded studies of pressure-induced superconductivity in nonsuperconductors by the discovery of superconducting transition in cerium with Tc = 1.8 K by applying isostatic pressure of P = 5 GPa. To date, the pressure-induced superconductivity has been detected in dozens of elements and compounds compressed at megabar pressures <ref type="bibr" target="#b1">[2]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[4]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b4">[5]</ref><ref type="bibr">[6]</ref><ref type="bibr">[7]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b5">[8]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b6">[9]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b7">[10]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b8">[11]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b9">[12]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b10">[13]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b11">[14]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b12">[15]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b13">[16]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b14">[17]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b15">[18]</ref>, including milestone experimental discoveries of near-room-temperature (NRT) superconducting hydrides <ref type="bibr" target="#b1">[2]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[4]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b7">[10]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b8">[11]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b9">[12]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b10">[13]</ref>.</p><p>Desgreniers et al <ref type="bibr" target="#b16">[19]</ref> detected metallization of oxygen at pressures P &gt; 90 GPa, and this phase transformation from non-metallic -O2 phase into metallic -O2 phase has been studied for three decades <ref type="bibr" target="#b17">[20]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b18">[21]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b19">[22]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b20">[23]</ref>.</p><p>Shimizu et al <ref type="bibr" target="#b5">[8]</ref> reported that -O2 phase is a superconductor with transition temperature of Tc = 0.6 K at pressures in the range of P = 115-120 GPa. Shimizu et al <ref type="bibr" target="#b5">[8]</ref> also reported temperature dependent upper critical field data, Bc2(T), which we analyse herein with the purpose to classify superconductivity (i.e., conventional vs unconventional) in -O2 phase.</p><p>Primary demand to perform this classification is based on our recent findings that all NRT highly-compressed superconductors are, surprisingly enough, unconventional superconductors <ref type="bibr" target="#b21">[24]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b22">[25]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b23">[26]</ref>, which exhibit the ratio of the superconducting transition temperature, Tc, to the Fermi temperature, TF, in the range of 0.01 ≲ 𝑇 𝑐 𝑇 𝐹 ≲ 0.05, which is the range for all known unconventional superconductors <ref type="bibr" target="#b24">[27,</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b25">28]</ref>.</p><p>In result, we find that in all considered scenarios -O2 phase (P = 115 GPa) has Tc/TF ratio in the range of 0.008 ≲ 𝑇 𝑐 𝑇 𝐹 ≲ 0.107, and, thus, this highly-compressed phase of gaseous element should be classified as unconventional superconductor.</p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head>II. The upper critical field data analysis</head><p>Shimizu et al <ref type="bibr" target="#b5">[8]</ref> in their Fig. <ref type="figure">3</ref> reported experimental Bc2(T) data for -O2 phase at pressure P = 115 GPa which we fit to two models:</p><p>1. The first model was proposed by Baumgartner et al <ref type="bibr" target="#b26">[29]</ref>:</p><formula xml:id="formula_0">𝐵 𝑐2 (𝑇) = 𝜙 0 2•𝜋•𝜉 2 (0) • ( (1- 𝑇 𝑇 𝑐 )-0.153•(1- 𝑇 𝑇 𝑐 ) 2 -0.152•(1- 𝑇 𝑇 𝑐 ) 4 0.693 )<label>(1)</label></formula><p>where 𝜙 0 = 2.068 • 10 -15 Wb is magnetic flux quantum, and (0) is the ground state coherence length. We will designate this model as B-WHH model, because Eq.1 is analytical approximation of general model proposed by Werthamer, Helfand, and Hohenberg <ref type="bibr" target="#b27">[30]</ref>.</p><p>2. The second used model was proposed by Gor'kov <ref type="bibr" target="#b28">[31]</ref>:</p><formula xml:id="formula_1">𝐵 𝑐2 (𝑇) = 𝜙 0 2•𝜋•𝜉 2 (0) • ( 1.77-0.43•( 𝑇 𝑇 𝑐 ) 2 +0.07•( 𝑇 𝑇 𝑐 ) 4 1.77 ) • [1 -( 𝑇 𝑇 𝑐 ) 2 ]<label>(2)</label></formula><p>It should be noted, that both models (Eqs. 1,2) are in wide use at the moment to analyse experimental Bc2(T) data for whole variety of superconducting materials, ranging from atomically thin superconductors <ref type="bibr" target="#b29">[32]</ref> and practical superconductors <ref type="bibr" target="#b26">[29]</ref> to NRT superconductors <ref type="bibr" target="#b21">[24]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b22">[25]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b23">[26]</ref>.</p><p>Results of fit of Bc2(T) data for -O2 phase (P = 115 GPa) to Eqs. 1,2 are shown in Fig. <ref type="figure" target="#fig_0">1</ref> and deduced parameters are collected in Table <ref type="table">1</ref>.  </p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head>III. -O2 phase in Uemura plot</head><p>From known (0) and Tc values, the Fermi temperature, TF, can be calculated by an equation of the Bardeen-Cooper-Schrieffer (BCS) theory <ref type="bibr" target="#b30">[33]</ref>:</p><formula xml:id="formula_2">𝑇 𝐹 = 𝜀 𝐹 𝑘 𝐵 = 𝜋 2 8 • 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * • 𝜉 2 (0) • ( 𝛼•𝑘 𝐵 •𝑇 𝑐 ℏ ) 2 ,<label>(3)</label></formula><p>where α =  values for -O2 phase, to calculate TF for -O2 phase we chose a reasonable lower and upper bounds for these values. For lower bound of 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * we use the value for ambient pressure hydrogen-rich superconductor, PdHx <ref type="bibr" target="#b31">[34]</ref>:</p><formula xml:id="formula_3">𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * = 0.49 • 𝑚 𝑒 ,<label>(4)</label></formula><p>despite a fact that the closest (by Tc and by the atomic mass) ambient pressure superconductor to -O2 is the aluminium <ref type="bibr" target="#b32">[35]</ref> with</p><formula xml:id="formula_4">𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * = 1.0 • 𝑚 𝑒<label>(5)</label></formula><p>In this regard, in lower bound for 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * (Eq. 4) is chosen as intendent underestimated value to cover some hypothetical case that 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * might be reasonably low in -O2 phase. This lower bound for 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * can be also supported by 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * = (0.2 -0.5) • 𝑚 𝑒 reported by Medvedeva <ref type="bibr" target="#b33">[36]</ref> for multicomponent conducting oxides.</p><p>For the upper bound of 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 *</p><p>we use the highest value reported for highly compressed hydrides, 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * = 3.0 • 𝑚 𝑒 <ref type="bibr" target="#b34">[37]</ref>. The possibility for heavy effective charge carrier mass in -O2, i.e. 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * &gt; 3.0 • 𝑚 𝑒 , cannot be of course rejected a priori, but large effective masses, as a rule, always associated with strong interaction between spin and d-or f-orbitals, and the latter does not exist in such light elements, like oxygen. Thus, we do not consider a possibility that the effective mass can exceed mentioned above value of 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * = 3.0 • 𝑚 𝑒 .</p><p>The lowest value for</p><formula xml:id="formula_5">2•Δ(0)</formula><p>𝑘 𝐵 •𝑇 𝑐 is weak-coupling limit of 3.53 <ref type="bibr" target="#b30">[33]</ref>, and for all known s-wave superconductors <ref type="bibr" target="#b35">[38]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b36">[39]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b37">[40]</ref>  is limited by the upper bound of</p><formula xml:id="formula_6">2•Δ(0)</formula><p>𝑘 𝐵 •𝑇 𝑐 ≲ 5.0 <ref type="bibr" target="#b35">[38]</ref>. Thus, TF is calculated (Table <ref type="table">1</ref> and Fig. <ref type="figure" target="#fig_2">2</ref>) in the assumption that  is varying within a range of 3.53 ≤ 2•Δ(0) 𝑘 𝐵 •𝑇 𝑐 ≤ 5.0 (it should be noted, that this range is cover most highly-compressed hydrogenrich superconductors <ref type="bibr" target="#b21">[24,</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b34">[37]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b35">[38]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b36">[39]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b37">[40]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b38">[41]</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b39">[42]</ref>).</p><p>As the result, -O2 phase (P = 115 GPa) in all considered scenarios (Table <ref type="table">1</ref>) has 0.009 ≤ Tc/TF ≤ 0.108 and falls in unconventional superconductors band of the Uemura plot <ref type="bibr" target="#b24">[27,</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b25">28]</ref> (Fig. <ref type="figure" target="#fig_2">2</ref>). It should be stressed that primary physical reason, that -O2 phase is classified as unconventional superconductor is belong solid experimental result, that this superconductor exhibits relatively high ground state upper critical field, Bc2(0), and relatively low superconducting transition temperature, Tc. Truly, if -O2 phase will be conventional superconductor similar to Al (which exhibits 𝑇 𝑐 𝑇 𝐹 ⁄ = 8.4 • 10 -6 ), than in accordance with the expression <ref type="bibr" target="#b22">[25]</ref> based on BCS theory <ref type="bibr" target="#b30">[33]</ref>: </p><formula xml:id="formula_7">𝐵 𝑐2 ( 𝑇 𝑇 𝑐 = 0) = 𝜋•𝜙 0 •𝑘 𝐵 16•ℏ 2 • 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * • 𝛼 2 • ( 𝑇 𝑐 𝑇 𝐹 ) • 𝑇 𝑐 = 2.7 𝑚𝑇 (6)</formula><p>which is about two orders of magnitude larger than hypothetical value for a conventional superconductor.</p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head>V. Conclusions</head><p>In summary, in this paper we analyse experimental Bc2(T) data for superconducting -O2 phase of highly-compressed oxygen (P = 115 GPa), reported by Shimizu et al <ref type="bibr" target="#b5">[8]</ref>, and find that in all considered scenarios this highly-compressed -O2 phase is unconventional superconductor.</p></div><figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_0"><head>Figure 1 .</head><label>1</label><figDesc>Figure 1. Superconducting upper critical field, Bc2(T), data and fits to three models (Eqs. 1,2) for -O2 phase compressed at pressure of P = 115 GPa (raw data is from Ref. 8). (a) fit to B-WHH model, R = 0.9994; (b) fit to Gor'kov model, R = 0.998. 95% confidence bars are shown.</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_1"><head></head><label></label><figDesc>0.63 ± 0.01 K (0) = 42.0 ± 0.7 nm As there are no available experimental 𝛼 = 2•Δ(0) 𝑘 𝐵 •𝑇 𝑐 and the effective charge carrier mass 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 *</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_2"><head>Figure 2 .</head><label>2</label><figDesc>Figure 2. A plot of Tc versus TF where -O2 phase compressed at pressure of P = 115 GPa is shown together with the most representative superconducting families. Raw data is taken from [24-28]. Characteristic lines for the Bose-Einstein condensate (BEC), the Bardeen-Cooper-Schrieffer (BCS) superconductors and for Tc/TF = 1.0, 0.05, 0.01 are shown for clarity.</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_3"><head></head><label></label><figDesc>LaH 10 (annealed; P = 150 GPa) YH 4 +YH 6 (annealed; P = 186 GPa) ThH 9 (annealed; P = 170 GPa) ThH 10 (annealed; P = 174 GPa) H 3 S (annealed; P = 155-160 GPa) H 3 S (annealed; P = 155 GPa) H 3 S (annealed; P = 160 GPa) H 3 S (unannealed; P = 155 GPa) -O 2 phase (P = 115 GPa) Th 4 H 15 /Th 4 D 15 PdH x T c /T F = 1.0 T c /T F = 0.22 (BEC) T c /T F = 0.05 T c /T F = 0.01 T c /T F = 10 -3 (BSC)where for the simplicity we assumed that 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓 * = 1.0 • 𝑚 𝑒 and 𝛼 = 2•Δ(0) 𝑘 𝐵 •𝑇 𝑐 = 3.53 are identical to ones for aluminium. We note, that experimental value for -O2 phase<ref type="bibr" target="#b5">[8]</ref> is:</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="table" xml:id="tab_0"><head>Table I .</head><label>I</label><figDesc>Deduced and calculated parameters for -O2 phase compressed at pressure of P = 115 GPa. The smallest and the largest values for</figDesc><table><row><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell>𝑇 𝑐 𝑇 𝐹</cell><cell cols="2">are marked in bold.</cell></row><row><cell>Model</cell><cell>Deduced Tc (K)</cell><cell>Deduced (0) (nm)</cell><cell>(in 𝑚 𝑒 ) Assumed 𝑚 𝑒𝑓𝑓  *</cell><cell cols="2">𝑘 𝐵 •𝑇 𝑐 2•Δ(0) Assumed</cell><cell>TF (K)</cell><cell>Tc/TF</cell></row><row><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell>0.49</cell><cell cols="2">3.53</cell><cell>5.86 ± 0.02</cell><cell>0.108 ± 0.003</cell></row><row><cell>B-WHH</cell><cell>0.635 ± 0.008</cell><cell>41.3 ± 0.4</cell><cell>3.0</cell><cell cols="2">5.0 3.53</cell><cell>11.8 ± 0.02 35.9 ± 1.6</cell><cell>0.052 ± 0.002 0.018 ± 0.001</cell></row><row><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell cols="2">5.0</cell><cell>72.0 ± 3.2</cell><cell>0.009 ± 0.001</cell></row><row><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell>0.49</cell><cell cols="2">3.53</cell><cell>5.96 ± 0.40</cell><cell>0.106 ± 0.005</cell></row><row><cell>Gor'kov</cell><cell>0.63 ± 0.01</cell><cell>42.0 ± 0.7</cell><cell>3.0</cell><cell cols="2">5.0 3.53</cell><cell>12.0 ± 0.02 36.5 ± 2.5</cell><cell>0.053 ± 0.003 0.017 ± 0.001</cell></row><row><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell cols="2">5.0</cell><cell>73.3 ± 4.8</cell><cell>0.009 ± 0.001</cell></row></table></figure>
